data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);          // MSTest v3.8+
    // or: Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);        // older MSTest

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");           // add message for clarity
    // or with MSTest v3.8+ conditions:
    // CollectionAssert.That.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);                  // shows expected vs actual on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);                          // clearer intent + better failure message
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, x.Count)` | Shows "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent & message |

The general rule: prefer specific assertions (`AreEqual`, `IsNotNull`, `CollectionAssert`) over `Assert.IsTrue` because failure messages tell you *what went wrong* rather than just "expected true, got false."
